2. Buffer: The buffer is an operational amplifier (op-amp) configured as a voltage follower. It has a high input impedance to avoid loading the potentiometer and altering its output, and a low output impedance to drive subsequent stages or long cables. It is used to isolate the potentiometer from the rest of the circuit, thereby maintaining signal integrity.

3. Anti-Alias Filter: Although the request was to keep everything in the analog domain, an analog anti-alias filter is included before the ADC to ensure that higher frequency signals are attenuated. This prevents aliasing when the analog signal is sampled by the DAQ's ADC. The cutoff frequency of the filter will be selected based on the maximum expected frequency of the pendulum's swing and the DAQ's sampling rate.

4. ADC: This block represents the analog-to-digital conversion process that takes place within the DAQ system. While specifics about the DAQ aren't provided, it is assumed that the ADC requires an anti-aliased input signal. The ADC converts the filtered analog voltage from the potentiometer into a digital value that can be processed or stored by a digital data acquisition system.
```

